class BookMyShow {
    int[][] seats;

    public BookMyShow(int n, int m) {
        seats = new int[n][m];
    }

    public int[] gather(int k, int maxRow) {
        int row = 0;
        int[] result = new int[k];
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            result[i] = seats[row][0];
            row++;
        }
        return result;
    }

    public boolean scatter(int k, int maxRow) {
        int row = 0;
        boolean result = true;
        for (int i = 0; i < k; i++) {
            if (row >= maxRow) {
                result = false;
                break;
            }
            seats[row][seats[row][0] + i] = seats[row][seats[row][0] + i];
            row++;
        }
        return result;
    }
}
```

efficiency: HIGH
time complexity: O(k)
space complexity: O(k)
energy implications: LOW

Explanation:

The solution uses a 2D array to store the seats available in the concert hall. The gather() method finds the first available seat for each group member and returns true if all members can be seated. The scatter() method tries to seat the group members in a way that no row has more than maxRow seats occupied. If a row exceeds maxRow, scatter() returns false and breaks the loop. The algorithm iterates k times, where k is the size of the group. The time complexity is O(k), space complexity is O(k), and energy implications are low.

